  "prompt": "Can you describe the difference between 3G, 4G, and LTE in layman terms?",
  "response": "Here's a simple breakdown:\n\n3G (Third Generation):\n- First mobile network to enable internet browsing on phones\n- Slower internet speeds\n- Good for basic web browsing and email\n- Typical speeds around 1-2 Mbps\n- Think of it like a bicycle for internet connectivity\n\n4G (Fourth Generation):\n- Much faster than 3G\n- Better for streaming video and more complex internet tasks\n- Typical speeds around 10-20 Mbps\n- Like upgrading from a bicycle to a car\n\nLTE (Long-Term Evolution):\n- A type of 4G technology\n- Often marketed as \"4G LTE\"\n- Fastest and most advanced of the 3G/4G technologies\n- Typical speeds around 20-30 Mbps\n- Like upgrading from a car to a sports car\n\nIn practical terms, the progression went from:\n3G (slow) \u2192 4G (faster) \u2192 4G LTE (fastest)\n\nNow, 5G is emerging, which is even faster and more advanced, but that's beyond the scope of your original question.",
